Yes — absolutely. Once you change your amount to a BigDecimal in SctDebitData, you can convert it to a properly formatted string during the mapping. This will preserve the decimal part and let you store it in SctDebitPdfContent, which expects a string.

Here’s how you can do it:

private SctDebitPdfContent mapToContent(SctDebitData data) {
    SctDebitPdfContent content = new SctDebitPdfContent();
    content.setSupplierName(data.getSupplierName());
    content.setSupplierIban(data.getSupplierIban());
    content.setOutName(data.getOutName());
    content.setOutIban(data.getOutIban());
    content.setOutAddress(data.getOutAddress());

    if (data.getAmount() != null) {
        // Convert BigDecimal to string with 2 decimal places
        content.setAmount(data.getAmount().setScale(2, RoundingMode.HALF_UP).toString());
    } else {
        content.setAmount("0.00");
    }

    content.setExecutionDate(data.getExecutionDate());
    content.setLabel(data.getLabel());
    content.setEndToEndId(data.getEndToEndId());
    content.setTxId(data.getTxId());
    content.setControlKey(data.getControlKey());
    
    return content;
}

✅ Notes:
	1.	setScale(2, RoundingMode.HALF_UP) ensures that even numbers like 689 will become "689.00" in the string.
	2.	Using BigDecimal ensures no decimal precision is lost.

⸻

